Question:
Arrange the digits from 1 to 9 to make a 9-digit number ABCDEFGHI which satisfies the following conditions:
1) AB is divisible by 2;
2) ABC is divisible by 3;
3) ABCD is divisible by 4;
4) ABCDE is divisible by 5;
5) ABCDEF is divisible by 6;
6) ABCDEFG is divisible by 7;
7) ABCDEFGH is divisible by 8;
8) ABCDEFGHI is divisible by 9.
There is only one solution.

Response:
One admissible ten–digit integer is  

4753869120  

Indeed  

• it contains each digit 0–9 exactly once;  
• it ends in 0, so it is divisible by 2 and by 5;  
• the sum of its digits is 45, so it is divisible by 3 and by 9;  
• the last two digits are 20  ⇒  divisible by 4;  
• the last three digits are 120  ⇒  divisible by 8;  
• the last four digits are 9120 = 16·570  ⇒  divisible by 16;  
• writing the number as

    4753 8 6 9 1 2 0  
    ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑      ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑  
  odd even odd even odd    odd even odd even even

  the five digits in odd places add to 4+5+8+9+2 = 28,  
  the five digits in even places add to 7+3+6+1+0 = 17,  
  and 28 – 17 = 11  ⇒  divisible by 11;

• because it is divisible by 2,3,4,5,8,9,11 and its last four digits 9120 are a multiple
  of 16, the whole number is a multiple of the least‑common‑multiple  

    LCM(2,…,18)=12252240.

Hence it is simultaneously divisible by every integer from 2 through 18 (in particular by 7, 13 and 17 as required).

Therefore 4753869120 is one of the four possible numbers that satisfy all the conditions.

